Find the unexpected.

Over the last days I had many conversations about various topics around @instagram. I guess we are all here to share our work, connect and seek inspiration for future adventures and propel our own work further. At least that's how it is for me. Having said that, I'm not sure if this is just some sort of illusion we all create for ourselves. Do we really explore or do we just drive to famous churches in the Dolomites, take a quick picture and press on to the next spot everyone knows already? I understand why we are doing that; it generates a lot of engagement. I'm not saying we shouldn't visit famous places anymore or anything like that. I shared the exact church I'm referring to here in my feed myself. I spent a lovely evening with my dad and brother there which I wouldn't wanna miss for the world. But I hope that it becomes a little more possible to grow and reach more people with truly adventurous and inspiring posts with actual stories behind it instead of ticking off one famous spot after the other. I would love for us to go out and live up to the ideas we put out there about what this platform is. Just my two cents. Btw; I had loads of fun wandering around the alps and randomly ending up in this amazing canyon.
Enjoy your weekend and keep rocking! .

BEST OF 2017 - NO. 2
.
My favorite morning of 2017 by a country mile! It was a rainy Tuesday last summer and I couldn't have asked for more. I just finished a very stressful week and decided to just go by myself to find some peace and calm. While I really enjoy exploring with awesome people sometimes roaming around alone is just what i need. It calms me down and relaxes me like nothing else does. On that particular morning i was all alone at this place as it rained a lot and was fairly cold for a summers day. At some point i was so excited I videochatted my mom to show her the place. Something I usually don't do when shooting. 😂😂 But oh well it was a day to remember.

Got up around 2.30am to catch the sunrise at this magnificent castle together with @davidkratz_. It turned out to be too foggy for a proper sunrise though. Shortly after I took this shot the castle was completely invisible and fully covered in fog.
I'm still pretty excited though with what we got to see. Such a beautiful building covered in fog, the silence so early in the morning, the world just starting to wake up... for a brief second, all was well.

Rising straight up out of the stormy sea where the Atlantic meets the Arctic Ocean, the North Cape plateau stands 300m tall and is known as "the end of the world." It is just 2000km away from the North Pole and traditionally labelled the Northernmost tip of the European continent (although Knivskjelloden is about 1km further north).
Standing literally at the edge of the European continent gave me loads of goose bumps and was was just a mind blowing experience. It was a very special moment - certainly one of my favorites in 2017 🇳🇴

My greatgranddad is turning 100 years old today!
Born in 1917 he was alive for the first telephone being installed in his home town, both World Wars, German chancellor Brandt kneeling down in Warsaw asking for forgiveness, the unification of Germany, the birth of his son, his grandson and two greatgrandsons and so much more. Incredible.
One of the more special moments with my greatgranddad happened not long ago when we both crossed the Arctic Circle for the first time in our lives right as the sun rose during a cruise up the Norwegian coast we did together. It was one of those moments where everything lined up perfectly.
Happy birthday Opa!

Winterwonderland is here!
I wanted to visit this place for a long time and I am so happy I managed to explore this incredible UNESCO world heritage site last week. Getting there was a little adventure in itself already as the primary road to get near it was closed due to heavy snow and I had to go another route. I randomly saw a super tiny sign in one of the villages I drove through, parked there and just started walking. I couldn't see where I was going because of the thick snow covering the entire area and only after a solid 30 minute walk through the mountain (could have easily been some sort of field) I found the first sign pointing towards the viaduct. It was loads of fun not to get lost on some field in Graubünden and finally visit this epic piece of architecture. Totally worth the trip. Agreed? 🇨🇭

Behind the scenes.
Last week, when I visited the Dolomites for the first time, I went on a daddy-son-hike up to Seceda. With the lift closed between skiing and hiking season we walked all the way up there. We were the only people around for miles. It was such a cool experience overlooking the massive rocks of Seceda after climbing up there ourselves. Sometimes doing it yourself and not taking the easy way feels so much more rewarding. Thanks dad for coming with me even though you're not a big hiker. And for snapping this one while I was checking out angles to set up my tripod. Love, Jan.
